, United States; MacNeil, M.A., School of Marine Science and Technology, Newcastle University, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, United Kingdom, National Research Council, NOAA Panama City Laboratory, Panama City Beach, FL, United States; Wilson, S.K., School of Marine Science and Technology, Newcastle University, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, United Kingdom, ARC Centre of Excellence for Coral Reef Studies, James Cook University, Townsville, QLD, United States; Polunin, N.V.C., School of Marine Science and Technology, Newcastle University, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, United Kingdom; Jennings, S., Centre for Environment, Fisheries and Aquaculture Science, Lowestoft Laboratory, Lowestoft, United Kingdom, School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich, United Kingdom; Chabanet, P., Institut de Recherche pour le Développement, Nouméa, New Caledonia, Laboratoire d'Ecologie Marine (ECOMAR), Université de La Réunion, Saint-Denis, La Réunion, France; Clark, S., Natural England, Bridgewater House, Whitworth Street, Manchester, United Kingdom; Spalding, M.D., The Nature Conservancy, Newmarket, United Kingdom; Letourneur, Y., Université de la Méditerranée, Centre d'Océanologie de Marseille, UMR CNRS 6540 DIMAR, Campus de Luminy, Marseille, France; Bigot, L., Laboratoire d'Ecologie Marine (ECOMAR), Université de La Réunion, Saint-Denis, La Réunion, France; Galzin, R., UMR 5244 CNRS-EPHE-UPVD, Ecosystémes Coralliens, Université de Perpignan, Perpignan, France; Öhman, M.C., Department of Zoology, Stockholm University, Stockholm, Sweden; Garpe, K.C., Department of Zoology, Stockholm University, Stockholm, Sweden; Edwards, A.J., School of Biology, Newcastle University, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, United Kingdom; Sheppard, C.R.C., University of Warwick, Department of Biological Sciences, Coventry, United Kingdom","Coral reefs have emerged as one of the ecosystems most vulnerable to climate variation and change. While the contribution of a warming climate to the loss of live coral cover has been well documented across large spatial and temporal scales, the associated effects on fish have not. Here, we respond to recent and repeated calls to assess the importance of local management in conserving coral reefs in the context of global climate change. Such information is important, as coral reef fish assemblages are the most species dense vertebrate communities on earth, contributing critical ecosystem functions and providing crucial ecosystem services to human societies in tropical countries. Our assessment of the impacts of the 1998 mass bleaching event on coral cover, reef structural complexity, and reef associated fishes spans 7 countries, 66 sites and 26 degrees of latitude in the Indian Ocean. Using Bayesian meta-analysis we show that changes in the size structure, diversity and trophic composition of the reef fish community have followed coral declines. Although the ocean scale integrity of these coral reef ecosystems has been lost, it is positive to see the effects are spatially variable at multiple scales, with impacts and vulnerability affected by geography but not management regime. Existing no-take marine protected areas still support high biomass of fish, however they had no positive affect on the ecosystem response to large-scale disturbance. This suggests a need for future conservation and management efforts to identify and protect regional refugia, which should be integrated into existing management frameworks and combined with policies to improve system-wide resilience to climate variation and change. © 2008 Graham et al.",,"animal community; article; Bayes theorem; biomass; bleaching; climate change; controlled study; coral; ecosystem resilience; ecosystem restoration; environmental protection; fish; global climate; Indian Ocean; large scale production; marine environment; nonhuman; seasonal variation; animal; Anthozoa; climate; ecosystem; food industry; greenhouse effect; growth, development and aging; Kenya; population density; sea; Tanzania; Anthozoa; Pisces; Vertebrata; sea water; Animals; Anthozoa; Climate; Conservation of Natural Resources; Ecosystem; Fisheries; Fishes; Greenhouse Effect; Indian Ocean; Kenya; Oceans and Seas; Population Density; Seawater; Tanzania",,,,,,"Walther, G.-R., Post, E., Convey, P., Menzel, A., Parmesan, C., Ecological responses to recent climate change (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 389-395; Hughes, T.P., Baird, A.H., Bellwood, D.R., Card, M., Connolly, S.R., Climate change, human impacts, and the resilience of coral reefs (2003) Science, 301, pp. 929-933; Hoegh-Guldberg, O., Mumby, P.J., Hooten, A.J., Steneck, R.S., Greenfield, P., Coral reefs under rapid climate change and ocean acidification (2007) Science, 318, pp. 1737-1742; Brown, B.E., Coral bleaching: Causes and consequences (1997) Coral Reefs, 16, pp. S129-S138; Gardner, T.A., Côté, I.M., Gill, J.A., Grant, A., Watkinson, A.R., Long-term region-wide declines in Caribbean corals (2003) Science, 301, pp. 958-960; Bruno, J.F., Selig, E.R., Regional decline of coral cover in the Indo-Pacific: Timing, extent, and subregional comparisons (2007) PLoS ONE, 2 (8), pp. e711. , doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0000711; Goreau, T., McClanahan, T., Hayes, R., Strong, A., Conservation of coral reefs after the 1998 global bleaching event (2000) Conserv Biol, 14, pp. 5-15; Bellwood, D.R., Hughes, T.P., Folke, C., Nystroöm, M., Confronting the coral reef crisis (2004) Nature, 429, pp. 827-833; McClanahan, T.R., Ateweberhan, M., Graham, N.A.J., Wilson, S.K., Sebastian, C.R., Western Indian Ocean coral communities: Bleaching responses and susceptibility to extinction (2007) Mar Ecol Prog Ser, 337, pp. 1-13; Hoegh-Guldberg, O., Climate change, coral bleaching and the future of the world's coral reefs (1999) Mar Freshw Res, 50, pp. 839-866; Sheppard, C.R.C., Predicted recurrences of mass coral mortality in the Indian Ocean (2003) Nature, 425, pp. 294-297; Jones, G.P., McCormick, M.I., Srinivasan, M., Eagle, J.V., Coral decline threatens fish biodive